the questions for the first part and...

00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:05.483
So the first question is for Caren.

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:09.380
So the question is how do you feel about

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:13.110
pressure on teachers in
elementary school grades,

00:04:13.110 --> 00:04:16.090
K, transitional K fours to eliminate

00:04:16.090 --> 00:04:18.783
playing class and emphasize academics.

00:04:20.593 --> 00:04:21.623
I think you have to come here.

00:04:29.813 --> 00:04:32.140
- Hi, good question, right?

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:34.180
So this is very much a
question that's being posed

00:04:34.180 --> 00:04:37.410
to developmental psychologists
today all the time, right.

00:04:37.410 --> 00:04:39.492
There's all these new sort
of academic pressures,

00:04:39.492 --> 00:04:42.040
things are sort of getting
pushed earlier and earlier,

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:43.520
there's less and less time for sort of

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:45.410
free and exploratory activities,

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:47.883
much more time spent on test preparation.

00:04:49.060 --> 00:04:50.620
I don't think that anyone would say

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:53.890
that this is a good idea per se.

00:04:53.890 --> 00:04:56.160
I mean I think that what we have seen

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:58.470
is that at least in the early school years

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:00.440
so in preschool in particular.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:02.620
Preschools have completely adopted

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:05.760
a play focused emphasis.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:07.760
To you this probably
seems totally natural now

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:10.466
because this is just the
way that we live our lives,

00:05:10.466 --> 00:05:12.090
we just assume that play
is precisely the work

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:14.320
of this early childhood
and I think that now

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:15.950
with the sort of new
science that's coming out

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:18.860
showing that playful learning
actually might continue

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:20.000
right to have these sorts of benefits

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.260
and even later on,
there's pressure being put

00:05:23.119 --> 00:05:24.650
on the education system to sort of combat

00:05:24.650 --> 00:05:25.790
the direction that we've gone in

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:28.050
which is the sort of college preparation

00:05:28.050 --> 00:05:30.400
that starts even as early as first grade

00:05:32.282 --> 00:05:33.907
so it's bad.

00:05:33.907 --> 00:05:35.490
(laughter)

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:37.270
But it's hard, right, it's
a really difficult problem

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:39.507
and I do think that right now

00:05:39.507 --> 00:05:40.996
it's part of the conversation and so it's

00:05:40.996 --> 00:05:42.583
certainly going to be adjusting.

00:05:42.583 --> 00:05:44.033
- I have another one for you.

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:47.680
So you said evidence of imagination

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:50.820
can be seen as soon as infants can speak.

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:53.010
Does neo natal imitation suggest

00:05:53.010 --> 00:05:56.143
that newborns imagine the
existence of other people.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:01.833
- Sorry.

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:06.060
Neo natal imitation does it suggest

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:08.163
that they're imagining other people,

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:10.940
I don't have an answer to that question.

00:06:10.940 --> 00:06:15.940
I don't know, I can't even
speculate on that question

00:06:16.191 --> 00:06:17.630
in fact, I'm not sure.

00:06:17.630 --> 00:06:19.780
So I think that generally what we think of

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:22.870
as neo natal movements right

00:06:22.870 --> 00:06:26.425
there's an interaction
between touch sensation

00:06:26.425 --> 00:06:29.090
from the mother and neo natal movement

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:30.760
also to sound right, and other kinds

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:33.010
of sensory inputs so
they're reacting, right

00:06:33.010 --> 00:06:35.630
in many ways to their tactile
and sensory environment

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:38.180
but I don't think that we can speculate

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:39.080
about imagination.

00:06:39.080 --> 00:06:42.350
We know that neonates learn right

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:45.610
so they can be exposed to
particular kinds of sounds

00:06:45.610 --> 00:06:49.150
for example in utero and afterwards

00:06:49.150 --> 00:06:51.430
show signs of recognizing those sounds

00:06:51.430 --> 00:06:52.810
in various learning contacts

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:54.480
there's some really
interesting and ingenious

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:56.740
ways of testing this, they also recognize

00:06:56.740 --> 00:07:01.620
the smell of fluids that were
taken from the mother as well

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:03.850
and so there's recognition
and there's learning

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:06.410
that happens neonatally but I don't know

00:07:06.410 --> 00:07:08.923
I can't comment on imagination.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:13.110
- So I'll just take
advantage that you are here,

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:15.070
I'll ask you another one.

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:20.807
How does a child
counterfactual cognition change

00:07:21.950 --> 00:07:24.423
as he or she acquires language?

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:30.910
- How does counterfactual cognition change

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:33.295
as they acquire language, right.

00:07:33.295 --> 00:07:36.100
So, it makes sense right that being able

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:38.410
to think about alternative possibilities

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:40.830
should be influenced by
having abstract concepts

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:43.401
and language gives us
those abstract concepts

00:07:43.401 --> 00:07:45.884
so as we acquire more
rich and complex language

00:07:45.884 --> 00:07:48.200
we're also able to think of more

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:50.100
rich and complex kinds
of narratives, right

00:07:50.100 --> 00:07:53.420
and so this in part probably explains

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:55.460
some of the developmental
changes that we see

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:58.030
from very very early sort
of proto kinds of pretense

00:07:58.030 --> 00:08:00.980
which is mostly just substitute
one object for another

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:04.370
to the very elaborate kinds
of pretense that we see

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:06.510
in middle childhood and adolescence

00:08:06.510 --> 00:08:08.390
where they're developing these societies

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:09.920
that have their own system of governance

00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:11.600
and rules and food and clothing

00:08:11.600 --> 00:08:14.370
I mean it's really
amazing the work out there

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:16.170
sort of documenting middle childhood

00:08:17.265 --> 00:08:18.220
and the kinds of
paracosms that they create

00:08:18.220 --> 00:08:20.793
and those things are dependent of course

00:08:20.793 --> 00:08:22.410
on a more mature language
and so it seems to me

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:24.932
that there's a relationship there.

00:08:24.932 --> 00:08:26.690
