00:08:37.170 --> 00:08:40.373
Why do people have different
levels of imagination?

00:08:43.530 --> 00:08:47.210
- Well you know there's certainly a lot

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:50.040
that might have that is attributable

00:08:50.040 --> 00:08:55.040
to the cultural and social
upbringing and pressures.

00:08:57.860 --> 00:09:01.750
Whether or not there're underlying
neurological differences

00:09:01.750 --> 00:09:06.750
that's maybe too murky
a thing that we haven't

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:10.880
been able to explore yet

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:16.640
but you know so in a lot
of educational theory

00:09:18.083 --> 00:09:20.380
that educational theories
are changing always

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:24.610
and evolving and culturally you see

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:27.820
these differences where some children

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:30.700
are encouraged to imagine more

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:32.210
and for longer periods of time

00:09:32.210 --> 00:09:35.640
and in other cultures you know it's like

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:37.420
childhood's over, get to work, you know

00:09:37.420 --> 00:09:38.620
kind of attitudes

00:09:41.090 --> 00:09:44.970
and so some of this
kind of spills over into

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:49.380
life in general as it's lived in adulthood

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:51.930
but even in those cases
you certainly always

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:55.360
have a kind of counter, you know

00:09:56.293 --> 00:09:58.010
counter examples of people who seem

00:09:58.010 --> 00:10:01.330
to go against the grain and
have this kind of ongoing

00:10:01.330 --> 00:10:04.320
imaginative capacity and you know

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:06.460
so then sometimes there
are these things like

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:08.820
you know where everyone's an artist,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:10.330
everyone can do all this stuff

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:12.090
and you know and I think that's also

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:14.370
kind of an oversimplification

00:10:14.370 --> 00:10:18.573
of the cognitive differences that we have.

00:10:20.260 --> 00:10:24.950
So we're mentally very diverse species

00:10:24.950 --> 00:10:28.960
and I think we should,

00:10:28.960 --> 00:10:31.420
we really should celebrate that diversity

00:10:31.420 --> 00:10:33.360
rather thank think that everybody

00:10:33.360 --> 00:10:36.060
should be everything all the time.

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:38.726
- But if you take like
science fiction writers

00:10:38.726 --> 00:10:41.350
from different cultures,

00:10:41.350 --> 00:10:43.950
is there something unique about them?

00:10:43.950 --> 00:10:45.520
- Well you certainly see that,

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:48.330
so he was asking if you
take science fiction writers

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:51.820
which is a group of imaginative people

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:54.222
that we spent some time talking with

00:10:54.222 --> 00:10:57.570
and is there something
different about them.

00:10:57.570 --> 00:10:59.040
Well I think one thing you see

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:00.380
is that there are different ways

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:02.890
in which they think about problems

00:11:02.890 --> 00:11:04.764
and so there might be these kind of

00:11:04.764 --> 00:11:07.960
practices that they have cultivated

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:10.670
or that they kind of
naturally kind of gravitated

00:11:10.670 --> 00:11:14.196
to which caused them
to think about problems

00:11:14.196 --> 00:11:17.240
in ways that are more orthogonal

00:11:17.240 --> 00:11:19.920
to how those problems
are typically approached

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:22.200
and it often means they they're kind of

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.470
really expand the context by which

00:11:24.470 --> 00:11:28.260
they place problems within
so they don't think of them

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:32.756
quite so instrumentally
from a singular perspective.

00:11:32.756 --> 00:11:36.470
They are often kind of read across

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:39.760
many different kinds of literatures

00:11:39.760 --> 00:11:42.640
or engage in many different
kinds of discourses

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:47.161
so historical, scientific,
you know humanistic,

00:11:47.161 --> 00:11:49.750
a bunch of different kinds of things

00:11:49.750 --> 00:11:51.670
and then the work that they do

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:54.690
comes up with a kind of original synthesis

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:56.820
out of those many different elements

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:00.470
and so you start to see those kinds

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:04.480
of characteristics and then
if the question is well

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:06.400
why do they have them, you know

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:10.600
that is a good question.

00:12:10.600 --> 00:12:12.954
(laughs)

00:12:12.954 --> 00:12:14.123
- So another one for you here.

00:12:17.263 --> 00:12:18.140
So I think I'll simplify that but

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:21.230
is imagination really humans

00:12:21.230 --> 00:12:24.070
is it present in different animals,

00:12:24.070 --> 00:12:25.540
there are evidence that perhaps

00:12:25.540 --> 00:12:27.830
chimpanzees even gorillas may have

00:12:27.830 --> 00:12:29.430
some kind of imagination

00:12:29.430 --> 00:12:31.140
and in this same context

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:33.003
what about artificial intelligence,

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:36.360
you can make a computer be creative

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:39.173
or have innovation, is it imagination?

00:12:41.310 --> 00:12:43.990
- Yeah, so you know I kind of indicated

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:45.240
a little bit the

00:12:46.480 --> 00:12:51.240
in my talk how much richer our theories

00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:54.580
of imagination can become when we

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:59.580
consider the imaginative
realms of the non human

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:04.080
and you know and this
isn't to kind of diminish

00:13:04.080 --> 00:13:09.080
the kind of unique
capabilities of homo sapiens

00:13:10.955 --> 00:13:13.970
but I think we start to really expand

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:16.450
our understanding of our own imaginations

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:19.530
by trying to recognize what the kind of

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:24.133
imaginative umwelt is of
other kinds of entities.

00:13:26.706 --> 00:13:29.840
You know I gave just some
kind of cheeky little examples

00:13:31.300 --> 00:13:33.840
but you know to then consider

00:13:33.840 --> 00:13:38.840
well what is the imagination
of a swarm of bees

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:43.990
and you know that has both
a kind of social dimension

00:13:43.990 --> 00:13:45.630
as well as an individual dimension

00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:48.840
is an interesting way to
kind of think about then

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:51.650
how does that relate to what we consider

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:53.563
our kind of social imagination.

00:13:55.560 --> 00:13:57.910
And then as it goes to this question

00:13:57.910 --> 00:14:02.610
of artificial intelligence that often,

00:14:02.610 --> 00:14:04.120
as I mentioned a little bit,

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:06.390
when we start to approach the notion

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:08.660
of constructing an artificial intelligence

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:12.650
we do so by thinking of it

00:14:12.650 --> 00:14:16.220
as modeling aspects of human intelligence

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:17.980
or human imagination.

00:14:17.980 --> 00:14:20.640
Well our models of that,
our own understanding

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:22.810
of what we're trying to model

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:27.030
is very limited fragmented and emergent

00:14:27.030 --> 00:14:29.876
and so to kind of think of that

00:14:29.876 --> 00:14:33.120
as the kind of beginning and end

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:36.238
of what an artificial imagination could be

00:14:36.238 --> 00:14:41.220
is a terrible limitation
on that possibility

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:42.950
and in fact what we might find

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:46.430
is the more kind of viable
artificial imagination

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:49.030
would be imagination that is as alien

00:14:49.030 --> 00:14:53.040
to the human imagination as
that swarm of bees imagination

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:54.733
is to the human imagination.

00:14:55.723 --> 00:14:57.360
So all of these things kind of you know

00:14:57.360 --> 00:14:59.103
considering how we might.

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:03.520
We need to continuously expand

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:06.820
our conceptions of what this kind of

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:09.220
human phenomena is in relationship

00:15:09.220 --> 00:15:13.697
to the rest of the biosphere
and the techno sphere

00:15:14.950 --> 00:15:17.383
that we're in the process of building.

